        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Cambridge Bible for Schools and Colleges",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "24–30",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "b",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") Provision for the custody of the votive gifts and offerings during the march",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "24",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "twelve of the chief of the priests",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] R.V. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "twelve of the chiefs of the priests",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Literally ‘twelve of the princes of the priests’. The R.V. margin adds, In ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Nehemiah 12:24",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Levites",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Sherebiah, Hashabiah",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] R.V. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "even Sherebiah, Hashabiah",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Marg. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "besides",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The exact meaning is not very evident.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "a",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") The A.V. follows the Vulgate, “et separavi de principibus sacerdotum duodecim, Sarabiam et Hasabiam et cum eis de fratribus eorum decem”. The preposition which in the original stands before ‘Sherebiah’ is then treated (as in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezra 8:16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") as the sign of the object. The objection to this is that Sherebiah and Hashabiah seem to have been Levites.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "b",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") The LXX. translates the preposition as the sign of the dative, “And I assigned of the chiefs of the priests twelve unto Sherebiah, &c.” (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "καὶ διέστειλα",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " … ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "τῷ Σαραΐᾳ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). The objection to be made to this rendering is that it represents the priests as placed in a subordinate position to those who were Levites.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "c",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1Es 8:54",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and Eresibia (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "καὶ Ἐρεσιβίαν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") suggests another reading (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ו",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " for ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ל",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), “And I separated … twelve and Sherebiah, &c.”",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "d",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") The same result is obtained by the rendering of the R.V. margin, which is to be preferred, “I separated twelve of the chiefs of the priests, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "besides",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " Sherebiah, Hashabiah and ten of their brethren with them”, i.e. 12 priests ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "in addition to",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " 12 Levites (Sherebiah, Hashabiah and their 10 brethren). Accepting this rendering, we see that Ezra selected two groups of twelve, one of priests, the other of Levites, to act as guardians of the treasure, which agrees with ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezra 8:30",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The names of Sherebiah and Hashabiah are for some reason specially mentioned, either being the best known of the twenty-four, or perhaps alone recorded in the chronicle employed by the compiler. The only other explanation possible, that of the R.V. text, is that Sherebiah and Hashabiah were two of ‘the chiefs of the priests’ and not to be identified with the Levites of the same name in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Nehemiah 12:24",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". This gives a satisfactory meaning, according to which Ezra selected twelve ‘chiefs of priests’ to act as custodians. But (1) the clause ‘and ten of their brethren with them’, after the previous mention of the ‘twelve’, rather denotes a second group of the same number: (2) it is expressly stated in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezra 8:30",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ‘the priests ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "and the Levites",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " received the weight of the silver, &c.’, while according to the R.V. text the Levites were not of the number.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 24.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Then I separated twelve of the chief of the priests, Sherebiah, Hashabiah,",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " etc. Our translators, following the Vulgate, have omitted to render the preposition ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "hebrew",
        "text": "לְ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", which occurs in the Hebrew text before the name of Sherebiah, and have thus represented Sherebiah and Hashabiah as priests, whereas they were not priests, but Levites, as appears from vers. 18, 19. The true sense is given by the LXX. - \"Then I assigned twelve of the chief priests to Sherebiah, Hashabiah, and ten of their brethren; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "i.e.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " \"then I appointed twelve chief priests to act with twelve chief Levites, of whom Sherebiah and Hashabiah were two, in the matter of the royal offering.\" Ezra seems to have considered, that as the gift of Artaxerxes was an offering to the house of God, it ought to be handed over at once to the custody of the ministers of religion, and not remain in secular hands (compare ver. 28). Ezra 8:24",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
